ce:section.ce:para:
The blue emissions from the N-S-C-dots could be observed from root tissues when excited at 405nm (Fig. 6
                        ). There are many different regions of the imaging. We can observe that N-S-C-dots can easily enter the root hairs (Fig. 6a) and lateral roots (Fig. 6b). The cells of elongation zone in root are nearly cylindrical and more N-S-C-dots are localized in the cell membrane, which forms a clear cell outline (Fig. 6c). Vascular bundles in root tissues are used to transport water and inorganic salts, and N-S-C-dots with good solubility are widely converged to a narrow blue ribbon (Fig. 6d). However, it is difficult for N-S-C-dots to enter some vacuoles as dark areas shown in Fig. 6e. The reason may exist that vacuole is an organelle with high osmotic pressure and the liquid in vacuoles is maintained at a relatively isolated environment because of tonoplast [30]. N-S-C-dots can also be used to detect the metabolism of root tissue (Fig. 7
                        ). Lateral roots are incubated with the N-S-C-dots with the same concentration (300μg ml−1) and time (3h) but under the different temperatures: 4°C (Fig. 7a) and 20°C (Fig. 7b). A stronger fluorescence is observed under 20°C, indicating lateral roots absorb more water from the external environment at a higher temperature. During incubation with the N-S-C-dots, no morphological damage of the cells was observed, demonstrating their good biocompatibility and low cytotoxicity.
